{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17648721","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17648721"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:56:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:56:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18328"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18328","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18328"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.25,0.11,0.32,0.04,0.29]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11046"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74270"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11046","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11046"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18328"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59761"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"7437"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25629"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25633"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74270","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74270"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the purpose of a knee osteotomy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["To remove damaged cartilage from the knee joint","To fuse the knee joint to prevent movement","To replace the knee joint with an artificial implant","To inject medication directly into the knee joint","To realign the bones to shift weight away from the damaged area"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary purpose of a knee osteotomy is to \u003Cstrong\u003Erealign the bones to shift weight away from the damaged area\u003C/strong\u003E. This surgical procedure is often used to treat knee osteoarthritis by redistributing the load on the knee joint, thereby relieving pain and improving function. It can delay the need for a total knee replacement by preserving the natural joint.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETo remove damaged cartilage from the knee joint\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes a different procedure, such as arthroscopy\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETo replace the knee joint with an artificial implant\u003C/strong\u003E - This is a knee replacement surgery, not an osteotomy\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETo fuse the knee joint to prevent movement\u003C/strong\u003E - This is known as arthrodesis, not osteotomy\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETo inject medication directly into the knee joint\u003C/strong\u003E - This is typically done in procedures like corticosteroid injections, not osteotomy\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Osteotomy of the knee involves cutting and realigning bones to relieve pressure on the knee joint.","This procedure is often used to treat knee osteoarthritis by shifting weight away from the damaged area.","Osteotomy can delay the need for knee replacement surgery by preserving the natural joint."],"references":["Khurana, I., Khurana, A., \u0026 Kowlgi, N. G. (2019). Textbook of Medical Physiology_-E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Datta HK, Ng WF, Walker JA, Tuck SP, Varanasi SS. The cell biology of bone metabolism. J Clin Pathol. 2008 May;61(5):577-87. doi: 10.1136/jcp.2007.048868. PMID: 18441154","Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Smith, R., \u0026 Wordsworth, P. (2016). Oxford textbook of clinical and biochemical disorders of the skeleton. Oxford University Press"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59761"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18328"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59761","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59761"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-25T04:05:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-25T04:05:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11046"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74270"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4931"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"